I would leverage the [`token_count` data type](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/token-count.html). In your index, you can add a sub-field of type `token_count` to your `title` and `content` fields, like this:

    PUT web
    {
      &quot;mappings&quot;: {
          &quot;properties&quot;: {
            &quot;title&quot;: {
              &quot;type&quot;: &quot;text&quot;,
              &quot;fields&quot;: {
                &quot;length&quot;: {
                  &quot;type&quot;: &quot;token_count&quot;,
                  &quot;analyzer&quot;: &quot;standard&quot;
                }
              }
            },
            &quot;content&quot;: {
              &quot;type&quot;: &quot;text&quot;,
              &quot;fields&quot;: {
                &quot;length&quot;: {
                  &quot;type&quot;: &quot;token_count&quot;,
                  &quot;analyzer&quot;: &quot;standard&quot;
                }
              }
            }
          }
        }
    }

Then, in order to find out the number of tokens, you can simply run a `sum` aggregation on the `.length` sub-field, like this:

    POST web/_search
    {
      &quot;size&quot;: 0,
      &quot;aggs&quot;: {
        &quot;title_tokens&quot;: {
          &quot;sum&quot;: {
            &quot;field&quot;: &quot;title.length&quot;
          }
        },
        &quot;content_tokens&quot;: {
          &quot;sum&quot;: {
            &quot;field&quot;: &quot;content.length&quot;
          }
        }
      }
    }

I am using data type called [token_count](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/token-count.html) It will calculate and store the count of tokens for each text. This count value can be utilized to get the token count of fields

