Timer callback functions run **after** the current instructions on the call stack are complete. The callback functions sit in the Event Queue and wait to be invoked by the JavaScript runtime.

Here&#39;s an example. Note that &quot;Job Complete&quot; will print to the console before the timer&#39;s callback message does. The callback will run AFTER the main thread is idle.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    console.log(&quot;About to set up the timer....&quot;);

    setTimeout(function(){
      console.log(&quot;Timer callback says &#39;Hello&#39;&quot;);
    }, 0);

    console.log(&quot;Job Complete&quot;);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

If you want the page to refresh at the end of the timer function, place that code at the end of the timer callback function, not *after* the timer function.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    console.log(&quot;About to set up the timer....&quot;);

    setTimeout(function(){
      console.log(&quot;Timer callback says &#39;Hello&#39;&quot;);
      console.log(&quot;Job Complete&quot;);  // &lt;-- Now, this will run at the end
    }, 0);



&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

And, more specifically, if you want to wait until an image is loaded to do something, just set up a `load` event handler for the image.

